            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Your well pump is arguably the most critical electrical component on a rural property—without it, you have no water for any household use. Document pump history: How old is your well pump? How many times has it failed or required service? Frequent failures often indicate electrical issues rather than pump problems. Check electrical protection: Does your well have dedicated surge protection? Is there a lightning arrestor at the control box? Rillito's exposed location and intense monsoon lightning makes protection essential. Unprotected pumps typically fail from lightning within 5-10 years, costing $2,500-6,000 for replacement. Verify circuit sizing: Well pump circuits must be properly sized for pump horsepower and wire run length. Undersized circuits cause voltage drop, reducing pump performance and shortening pump life. A ¾ HP pump typically needs 20-30 amp circuit; 1 HP pump needs 30 amp circuit; larger pumps may need more. Control box condition: Open the control box and inspect for corrosion, burned components, loose connections, or temporary repairs (wire nuts, electrical tape patches). These indicate degraded electrical requiring replacement. Grounding quality: Proper grounding is essential for lightning protection. Well electrical should have dedicated ground rods and bonding. Calculate protection investment vs. risk: Comprehensive well pump electrical protection typically costs $1,200-2,000 but prevents $3,000-6,000 pump replacement plus emergency service costs and days without water. For Rillito properties, it's not \"if\" lightning will strike nearby, but \"when.\""
